\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Facility location problems are among the most studied classes of
combinatorial optimization, with applications in logistics, supply chain
design, and public service planning~\citep{klose2005facility,laporte2019location}.
The \emph{Capacitated Facility Location Problem} (CFLP) asks for a
minimum-cost selection of facilities from a set of candidate sites,
together with an assignment of client demand to open facilities, subject
to capacity constraints.
In the \emph{multi-source} variant (MSCFLP) considered here, each
client's demand may be split across several open facilities---a natural
model for settings where a single supplier cannot economically serve an
entire account.
The MSCFLP is NP-hard and computationally challenging at large scale;
its LP relaxation, however, is notably tight because the
variable-upper-bound constraints $x_{ji} \leq d_i y_j$ are binding in
the LP, making the LP bound an accurate proxy for the integer optimum.

\paragraph{Kernel Search.}
Guastaroba and Speranza~\citep{guastaroba2012kernel} introduced a
Kernel Search (KS) matheuristic for the MSCFLP that exploits LP
relaxation information to decompose the full MILP into a sequence of
smaller, tractable subproblems.
Their framework identifies a \emph{kernel}---a subset of LP-open or
fractionally-open facilities---and an \emph{edge set} connecting kernel
facilities to clients.
A MILP restricted to this edge set is solved, followed by a bucket
expansion phase that iteratively adds LP-closed facilities and re-solves.
The key design choice determining solution quality and subproblem size
is \emph{how edges are selected}: Guastaroba and Speranza use a
reduced-cost threshold $\gamma$, including edge $(j,i)$ if
$\bar{c}_{ji} \leq \gamma$, where $\gamma$ is the mean reduced cost
over LP-positive $x$ variables.
This facility-centric, dual-based criterion connects each facility to
potentially many clients, producing subproblems whose size is
uncontrolled and grows with instance scale.
A practical consequence is that large instances require long MILP solve
times simply to establish a first feasible incumbent, before any
refinement can begin.

\paragraph{Our contribution.}
We propose \emph{Funnel Kernel Search} (FKS), a multi-stage
matheuristic that replaces the $\gamma$-threshold with a dual-based,
client-centric strategy.
The name captures the core mechanism: the algorithm plays multiple
rounds, each round removing chairs (reducing the edge set) while
allowing players (clients) to keep the seats they already occupy
(incumbent arcs).

The algorithm has three stages.
In Stage~1, a wide edge net ($k=50$ edges per client, selected by
lowest reduced cost) is solved with Gurobi's feasibility-first mode,
finding a strong incumbent quickly.
This criterion mirrors G\&K's $\gamma$-threshold---both select arcs
with low reduced cost---but bounds the subproblem size at exactly
$k|\I|$ edges regardless of instance scale.
In Stage~2, the edge set is rebuilt from the Stage~1 \emph{integer
allocation}: every arc used in the incumbent is preserved, and
remaining slots are filled to $k=20$ by reduced cost.
The Stage~1 solution is injected as a warm start, so Gurobi immediately
has a feasible point and focuses entirely on improvement.
Stage~3 repeats the same logic, tightening further to $k=10$.

This design has three properties that distinguish it from the
$\gamma$-threshold:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Bounded subproblem size.}
    Each stage uses at most $k|\I|$ edges, regardless of instance
    scale or LP density.
    The $\gamma$-threshold produces hundreds of edges per client on
    large instances; FKS produces exactly $k|\I|$.

  \item \textbf{Warm-start feasibility by construction.}
    Stage~2's edge set contains every arc used by the Stage~1
    incumbent, so the warm-started solution is immediately feasible.
    No feasibility search is needed; Gurobi jumps directly to
    improvement.

  \item \textbf{Integer-allocation feedback.}
    Edge sets in stages 2 and 3 are derived from the \emph{integer}
    solution, not the LP relaxation.
    This targets the subproblem at what actually worked in the previous
    stage, converging faster than repeatedly re-deriving from the LP.
\end{enumerate}

Computational experiments on all 150 instances of the Test Bed~A
benchmark of Avella et al.~\citep{avella2008effective}---comprising up
to $2{,}000 \times 4{,}400$ instances at tight capacity
($\rho = 1.1$)---show that FKS achieves zero losses vs.\ the
Guastaroba--Speranza (2012) baseline across all families, with three
outright wins on the $1{,}000 \times 1{,}000$ family and a $5\times$
speedup on average.

\paragraph{Relation to concurrent work.}
Bakker et al.~\citep{bakker2025paks} independently propose a
Pattern-based Kernel Search (PaKS) for the \emph{single-source} CFLP
(SSCFLP), where each client must be assigned to exactly one facility.
PaKS gathers structural information by solving $N+1$ LP relaxations and
applying spectral biclustering to group locations and clients into
regions.
Our work differs in three ways: (i)~we target the MSCFLP, where the LP
relaxation is significantly tighter; (ii)~our edge selection adds zero
overhead beyond the single LP solve already required by KS; and
(iii)~we measure solution quality against the LP lower bound, providing
a tighter certificate of near-optimality.

\paragraph{Paper structure.}
Section~\ref{sec:formulation} states the MSCFLP formally and analyzes
LP solution structure.
Section~\ref{sec:algorithm} describes the FKS algorithm in full.
Section~\ref{sec:experiments} presents computational results on
Test Bed~A.
Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.
